SIMPLE: unbend
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Unbend
<hw>Un*bend"</hw> <pr>(⟦ucr⟧n*b⟦ecr⟧nd")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Unbent</conjf>
<pr>(⟦ucr⟧n*b⟦ecr⟧nt")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Unbending</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[1st pref. <ets>un-</ets> +
<ets>bend</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To free from flexure; to make,
or allow to become, straight; to loosen; <as>as, to <ex>unbend</ex> a
bow</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A remit from a strain or from exertion; to set at
ease for a time; to relax; <as>as, to <ex>unbend</ex> the mind from
study or care</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You do <qex>unbend</qex> your noble strength.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To unfasten, as
sails, from the spars or stays to which they are attached for use.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>To cast loose or untie, as a rope.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Unbend</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Unbend
<hw>Un*bend"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cease to be
bent; to become straight or relaxed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To relax in exertion, attention, severity, or the
like; hence, to indulge in mirth or amusement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Unbending</ent>⟦br⟧
